    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-04T18:00:00-05:00" n="191"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d191">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.4061 Motion Pictures/223: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marriner</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 4, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>396. Your despatch 2162.<note n="33" xml:id="d191fn33">Despatch No. 2162,
                        September 12; not printed.</note> You are requested to make formal inquiry
                    of the French Government concerning the nature of the proposed <pb facs="0316"
                        n="240" xml:id="pg_240"/> film decree on the grounds that press reports and
                    rumors indicate that American film interests may be materially injured by its
                    provisions.</p>
                <p>For your information, in connection with the trade agreement we have requested
                        (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) permits to show 100 dubbed films; (<hi
                        rend="italic">b</hi>) permits to show original version films in 10 theaters
                    in Paris and 20 theaters in other departments; (<hi rend="italic">c</hi>) quota
                    of 93,900 kilograms. The proposed decree would have the effect of making any
                    valuable concession on films impossible, thus jeopardizing the whole trade
                    agreement.</p>
                <p>You may use your discretion as to whether to make representations to the French
                    authorities verbally or in writing but you are requested to impress
                    energetically upon them the lamentable effect the promulgation of such a decree
                    during trade negotiations would have upon American opinion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
